        When I started my last company, I joined several friends who were also female business owners for a monthly dinner to share and receive support from each other. This really helped me emotionally but often none of us had the appropriate experience to guide each other professionally. I also joined some mentoring groups sponsored by local business organizations in my geographic area. One particular organization connected me with a female executive every quarter so I could ask questions such as, “How do I set up an Employee Stock Ownership Plan (ESOP)?” I did get useful advice but since the executives were volunteer mentors, I never felt I got enough personal attention.<br>
        <br>
        Along the course of growing our company, I met Marshall. He was referred to me from one of our investors and he became our Executive Mentor and my trusted advisor. We started a contract where he spent 20 hours a month advising us. What a difference this made for me and our company! Someone was now focused on my personal and professional growth and the future of our company; he provided me with important advice on the steps I needed to take at each stage of our lifecycle. Ultimately, he mentored us through our recovery from the Dot-Com Bust to rebuild our company and sell it to a large multinational company. What an amazing and valuable relationship! This was my first experience with a Subject Matter Expert who had experience with general management strategy and growth in our market of government services.<br>
        <br>
        It took me five years to find a SME to help me run, grow, and ultimately sell our last company. According to the U.S. Small Business Administration Office of Advocacy, about half of new businesses go out of business in the first five years[1]. Our company was lucky to have survived long enough to find our SME.<br>
